label.appnav.dashboard.section.api.key.t: 要获取API密钥，请将应用程序添加到Portal。 门户网站为每个注册的应用程序分配唯一的API密钥。 应用程序需要API密钥来访问API。 您还需要一个API密钥来测试API资源管理器中的API。
Find APIs that are appropriate for apps that you're building.
To monitor the usage and latency of your APIs, use the Portal's Real-Time Analytics. Quickly visualize traffic trends for APIs and applications. Track quota usage for organizations. Developers have access only to information specific to their organization.
label.appnav.dashboard.section.publish.a: The Add API Wizard provides an easy way to publish your existing APIs on the Portal. Before you publish any APIs, you need to create a EULA that you will associate with the APIs. Also, please ensure that your API backend is CORS enabled before you publish any APIs.
The API Explorer lets you interact with APIs that have swagger or wadl files. You also need an application's API key to interact with APIs.
label.appnav.dashboard.tagline: 安全地向开发人员公开API，同时向他们提供所需的所有工具和资源，以便根据您的API快速构建应用程序。
label.appnav.dashboard.test.drive: After you've published an API take it for a test drive in the API Explorer.
label.appnav.dashboard.text.api.key.how: To get an API key, add an application to the Portal. The Portal assigns each registered application a unique API key. Applications need an API key to access APIs. You also need an API key to test APIs in the API Explorer.
APIs are registered in the API Catalog, where you can reference, filter, and search for APIs.
label.appnav.dashboard.text.manage.organ: In the Portal, all developers are members of developer organizations. When Portal administrators add an organization, they give it an account plan, which controls API quotas, rate limits, and access to private APIs.
label.appnav.dashboard.text.manage.users: Administrators can enroll users and assign them any role. Developers can register themselves if third-party registration is turned on. The registration request workflow lets administrators manage registration requests from developers.
label.appnav.dashboard.text.not.seeing: Not seeing what you're looking for? Check out our
The Add API Wizard provides an easy way to publish your existing APIs on the Portal. Before you publish any APIs, you need to create a EULA that you will associate with the APIs. Also, please ensure that your API backend is CORS enabled before you publish any APIs. If you want to provide interactive API documentation in the API Explorer, then you need a Swagger or WADL file for each API you publish. After publishing an API, it will have a Pending Sync State for up to a minute. Please wait until the API synchronizes to the proxy before you use the API.
label.appnav.dashboard.text.restrict.acc: To control which developer organizations can access an API, you can make the API private and include it in an account plan. Only organizations with that account plan can access the private API. Account plans also control API quotas and rate limits.
label.appnav.dashboard.text.test.api.how: The API Explorer lets you interact with APIs that have swagger or wadl files. You also need an application's API key to interact with APIs.
label.appnav.dashboard.text.troubleshoot: Real-time analytics can help you understand API latencies and quota usage, as well as general API and application traffic.
label.appnav.dashboard.text.try.api.how: The API Explorer lets you interact with APIs, obtain live responses, and generate code samples. You need an API key to interact with APIs in the API Explorer.
label.appnav.dashboard.text.work.with.ap: Every time an application calls an API, it must include its unique API key in the message. To get an API key, create an application in the Portal.
label.appnav.dashboard.track.performance: Measure and track the performance of your APIs.
label.appnav.dashboard.video.api.key.tit: How to get an API key

label.trial.add.app.content.step1: On the Organization tab, select the organization. Organization administrators don't have this tab.
label.trial.add.app.content.step2: On the Information tab, enter a name and description.
label.trial.add.app.content.step3: On the API Management tab, add APIs.
label.trial.add.app.content.step4: On the Auth tab, if any of the added APIs use OAuth, specify the callback/redirect URL and scope. Set the type to public or confidential.
label.trial.add.app.content.step5: On the Auth tab, if mobile SSO is enabled on the Portal, you can enable MSSO for the application.
label.trial.discover.api.content.step1: Click the Filters button to filter/search the list of APIs.
label.trial.discover.api.content.step2: To request access to an API, you need to first get an API key.
label.trial.discover.api.content.step3: To read more about or test an API, you have to go to
label.trial.publish.api.content.step1: On the Organization tab, optionally select an organization.
label.trial.publish.api.content.step2: On the Details tab, enter an API name and version. Select a EULA.
label.trial.publish.api.content.step3: On the Proxy Configuration tab, complete the proxy URL (the API's public URL). Enter the API's location (where the API Proxy routes requests from applications). Select a policy template and its parameters.
label.trial.publish.api.content.step4: On the API Metadata tab, upload a WADL or Swagger file for the API. Select the default authentication type that is used when testing the API with API Explorer. Enter public and private API descriptions.
label.trial.test.api.content: The Swagger file allows you to interactively query the live backend API as well as generate code samples for your application.
